{"title_page": "Kiryat Ye'arim", "text_new": "{{for|the youth village|Kiryat Ye'arim Youth Village}}\n{{Infobox Israel municipality\n|name          = Kiryat Ye'arim\n|image_skyline = Kiryat Ye'arim.jpg\n|image_caption = [[Beth midrash]] in Kiryat Ye'arim\n|hebname       = {{Hebrew|\u05e7\u05b4\u05e8\u05b0\u05d9\u05b7\u05ea \u05d9\u05b0\u05e2\u05b8\u05e8\u05b4\u05d9\u05dd}}\n|ISO           = Qiryat Y\u02c1arim\n|meaning       = Town of forests\n|founded= \n|type          = lc\n|typefrom= \n|altUnoSp      = Kiryat Yearim\n|country       = israel\n|district      = jerusalem\n|popyear       = {{Israel populations|Year}}\n|population    = {{Israel populations|Qiryat Ye'arim}}\n|population_footnotes = {{Israel populations|reference}}\n|area_dunam= \n|areakm= \n|pushpin_map   = Israel jerusalem#Israel\n|pushpin_label_position = left\n|coordinates   = {{coord|31|48|13.53|N|35|6|9.03|E|region:IL|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n|mayor         = Yitzhak Ravitz\n}}\n'''Kiryat Ye'arim''' ({{lang-he-n|\u05e7\u05b4\u05e8\u05b0\u05d9\u05b7\u05ea \u05d9\u05b0\u05e2\u05b8\u05e8\u05b4\u05d9\u05dd}}), also known as '''Telz-Stone''', is an [[Haredi Judaism|ultra-Orthodox]] [[local council (Israel)|town]] in the [[Jerusalem District]] of [[Israel]]. It is located in the approximate area of an ancient place mentioned in the Bible, from which it takes its name. It is bordered on one side by the [[Muslim]] [[Arab]] village of [[Abu Ghosh]], and on the other side by the [[secular]] [[Jewish]] community of [[Neve Ilan]].<ref name=\"nbn.org.il\">[http://www.nbn.org.il/aliyahpedia/community-housing/community-profiles/telz-stone-kiryat-yearim/ Community Profiles: Telz-Stone/Kiryat Yearim]</ref> In {{Israel populations|Year}} it had a population of {{Israel populations|Qiryat Ye'arim}}.\n\n==Geography==\nKiryat Ye'arim is located approximately {{convert|10|km|mi}} [[west]] of [[Jerusalem]], just [[north]] of the [[Tel Aviv]] \u2013 [[Jerusalem]] [[highway]]. Neighboring Kiryat Ye'arim to the northeast is the [[Arab]] town of Abu Ghosh. Kiryat Ye'arim is between 661.8 and 749.5 [[meters]] above [[sea level]].<ref name=\"profile\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cbs.gov.il/publications/local_authorities2005/pdf/638_1137.pdf|title=Local Authorities in Israel 2005, Publication #1295 - Municipality Profiles - Kiryat Ye'arim|publisher=Israel Central Bureau of Statistics|accessdate=2008-02-16|language=Hebrew}}</ref>\n\n==Biblical connection==\n===Kiriath-Jearim in the Hebrew Bible===\nThe modern town of Kiryat Ye'arim (Town of Forests) is named for [[Kiriath-Jearim]], mentioned in the [[Bible]] as the site where the [[Ark of the Covenant]] has been kept for 20 years, according to the [[Book of Samuel]]. From here the Ark was taken to [[Jerusalem]] by [[King David]] ({{Bibleref2|I Chronicles 13, 5-8}}).{{cn|date=September 2019}}\n\n==History==\nSix hundred [[dunams]] of modern-day Kiryat Ye'arim were purchased before 1948 by Menashe Elissar, a businessman who was attracted to the site as the location of the biblical Kiryat Ye'arim.<ref>[http://www.haaretz.com/israel-news/business/real-estate/.premium-1.579772 The Plot Thickens in Saga Between Hollywood Has-been and Haredi Community]</ref>\n\nThe modern community was established in 1973<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=mmYcJxEB9j8C&pg=PA102 Itineraries in Conflict: Israelis, Palestinians, and the Political Lives of Tourism, Rebecca L. Stein]</ref> by a group of students and teachers from [[Telshe yeshiva|Yeshivat Telz]] in America. Despite the official name of \"Kiryat Yearim\", it is widely known as Telz-Stone, after the yeshiva and [[American Greetings]] founder-chairman [[Irving I. Stone]], who helped to finance the community's early development.<ref name=\"nbn.org.il\"/>\n\n==Demography==\nAccording to the [[Israel Central Bureau of Statistics]] ([[CBS]]), at the end of 2005 Kiryat Ye'arim had a population of 3,100, predominantly [[Jew]]ish, with a growth rate of 1.2%. Many of the residents are immigrants from North America, Europe and South Africa.\n\n==Institutions==\nKiryat Ye'arim is home to three [[Orthodox Judaism|Orthodox]] post-high school [[yeshiva]]s aimed at foreign students, particularly from the U.S.: [[Yeshivas Neveh Zion|Neveh Zion]], Keser Dovid and Yishrei Lev.<ref>{{cite web|title=Kiryat Yearim (Telz-Stone)|url=http://www.nbn.org.il/aliyahpedia/community-housing-aliyahpedia/community-profiles/telz-stone-kiryat-yearim/|website=Nefesh B'Nefesh - Aliyahpedia|accessdate=19 April 2016|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nAlso, it's home to a [[Sephardic Haredim|Sephardic]] [[Haredi]] [[yeshiva]] - Be'er Yitzhak and another yeshiva: [[Me'orot Hatorah]].\n\n<br />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Jerusalem District}}\n\n[[Category:Local councils in Israel]]\n[[Category:Local councils in Jerusalem District]]\n[[Category:Populated places established in 1973]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|the youth village|Kiryat Ye'arim Youth Village}}\n{{Infobox Israel municipality\n|name          = Kiryat Ye'arim\n|image_skyline = Kiryat Ye'arim.jpg\n|image_caption = [[Beth midrash]] in Kiryat Ye'arim\n|hebname       = {{Hebrew|\u05e7\u05b4\u05e8\u05b0\u05d9\u05b7\u05ea \u05d9\u05b0\u05e2\u05b8\u05e8\u05b4\u05d9\u05dd}}\n|ISO           = Qiryat Y\u02c1arim\n|meaning       = Town of forests\n|founded= \n|type          = lc\n|typefrom= \n|altUnoSp      = Kiryat Yearim\n|country       = israel\n|district      = jerusalem\n|popyear       = {{Israel populations|Year}}\n|population    = {{Israel populations|Qiryat Ye'arim}}\n|population_footnotes = {{Israel populations|reference}}\n|area_dunam= \n|areakm= \n|pushpin_map   = Israel jerusalem#Israel\n|pushpin_label_position = left\n|coordinates   = {{coord|31|48|13.53|N|35|6|9.03|E|region:IL|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n|mayor         = Yitzhak Ravitz\n}}\n'''Kiryat Ye'arim''' ({{lang-he-n|\u05e7\u05b4\u05e8\u05b0\u05d9\u05b7\u05ea \u05d9\u05b0\u05e2\u05b8\u05e8\u05b4\u05d9\u05dd}}), also known as '''Telz-Stone''', is an [[Haredi Judaism|ultra-Orthodox]] [[local council (Israel)|town]] in the [[Jerusalem District]] of [[Israel]]. It is located in the approximate area of an ancient place mentioned in the Bible, from which it takes its name. It is bordered on one side by the [[Muslim]] [[Arab]] village of [[Abu Ghosh]], and on the other side by the [[secular]] [[Jewish]] community of [[Neve Ilan]].<ref name=\"nbn.org.il\">[http://www.nbn.org.il/aliyahpedia/community-housing/community-profiles/telz-stone-kiryat-yearim/ Community Profiles: Telz-Stone/Kiryat Yearim]</ref> In {{Israel populations|Year}} it had a population of {{Israel populations|Qiryat Ye'arim}}\n\n==Geography==\nKiryat Ye'arim is located approximately {{convert|10|km|mi}} [[west]] of [[Jerusalem]], just [[north]] of the [[Tel Aviv]] \u2013 [[Jerusalem]] [[highway]]. Neighboring Kiryat Ye'arim to the northeast is the [[Arab]] town of Abu Ghosh. Kiryat Ye'arim is between 661.8 and 749.5 [[meters]] above [[sea level]].<ref name=\"profile\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cbs.gov.il/publications/local_authorities2005/pdf/638_1137.pdf|title=Local Authorities in Israel 2005, Publication #1295 - Municipality Profiles - Kiryat Ye'arim|publisher=Israel Central Bureau of Statistics|accessdate=2008-02-16|language=Hebrew}}</ref>\n\n==Biblical connection==\n===Kiriath-Jearim in the Hebrew Bible===\nThe modern town of Kiryat Ye'arim (Town of Forests) is named for [[Kiriath-Jearim]], mentioned in the [[Bible]] as the site where the [[Ark of the Covenant]] has been kept for 20 years, according to the [[Book of Samuel]]. From here the Ark was taken to [[Jerusalem]] by [[King David]] ({{Bibleref2|I Chronicles 13, 5-8}}).{{cn|date=September 2019}}\n\n==History==\nSix hundred [[dunams]] of modern-day Kiryat Ye'arim were purchased before 1948 by Menashe Elissar, a businessman who was attracted to the site as the location of the biblical Kiryat Ye'arim.<ref>[http://www.haaretz.com/israel-news/business/real-estate/.premium-1.579772 The Plot Thickens in Saga Between Hollywood Has-been and Haredi Community]</ref>\n\nThe modern community was established in 1973<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=mmYcJxEB9j8C&pg=PA102 Itineraries in Conflict: Israelis, Palestinians, and the Political Lives of Tourism, Rebecca L. Stein]</ref> by a group of students and teachers from [[Telshe yeshiva|Yeshivat Telz]] in America. Despite the official name of \"Kiryat Yearim\", it is widely known as Telz-Stone, after the yeshiva and [[American Greetings]] founder-chairman [[Irving I. Stone]], who helped to finance the community's early development.<ref name=\"nbn.org.il\"/>\n\n==Demography==\nAccording to the [[Israel Central Bureau of Statistics]] ([[CBS]]), at the end of 2005 Kiryat Ye'arim had a population of 3,100, predominantly [[Jew]]ish, with a growth rate of 1.2%. Many of the residents are immigrants from North America, Europe and South Africa.\n\n==Institutions==\nKiryat Ye'arim is home to three [[Orthodox Judaism|Orthodox]] post-high school [[yeshiva]]s aimed at foreign students, particularly from the U.S.: [[Yeshivas Neveh Zion|Neveh Zion]], Keser Dovid and Yishrei Lev.<ref>{{cite web|title=Kiryat Yearim (Telz-Stone)|url=http://www.nbn.org.il/aliyahpedia/community-housing-aliyahpedia/community-profiles/telz-stone-kiryat-yearim/|website=Nefesh B'Nefesh - Aliyahpedia|accessdate=19 April 2016|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nAlso, it's home to a [[Sephardic Haredim|Sephardic]] [[Haredi]] [[yeshiva]] - Be'er Yitzhak and another yeshiva: [[Me'orot Hatorah]].\n\n<br />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Jerusalem District}}\n\n[[Category:Local councils in Israel]]\n[[Category:Local councils in Jerusalem District]]\n[[Category:Populated places established in 1973]]\n", "name_user": "Baldersdod", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kiryat_Ye%27arim"}
